docs.abstract: President Trump’s stop — to observe a moment of silence without extended public remarks — appeared to be a last-minute addition to his calendar.
docs.snippet: President Trump’s stop — to observe a moment of silence without extended public remarks — appeared to be a last-minute addition to his calendar.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump briefly visited a national monument to the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. on Monday to lay a wreath below the towering statue of the slain civil rights leader.

headline.main: Trump Lays Wreath at Brief Visit to Martin Luther King Jr. Memorial

docs.abstract: A video featuring Democratic House candidates with national security credentials has drawn raves. But because of campaign finance laws, few have seen it.
docs.snippet: A video featuring Democratic House candidates with national security credentials has drawn raves. But because of campaign finance laws, few have seen it.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — It is one of the more compelling ads of the midterm election cycle, a 60-second video featuring eight Democratic women running for House seats, reciting their backgrounds in either the military or intelligence services as the predicate for their first runs for political office. Bruce Springsteen’s anthemic “The Rising” soars in the background.

headline.main: Great Ad. Compelling Characters. But No Mass Audience for the Democratic Candidates.
headline.print_headline: Ad That Pushes All the Right Buttons,  But Millions of Voters Will Never See It

docs.abstract: With many Republicans courting the president and others afraid to criticize him, an Ohio congressman has gingerly created a small crack in the wall, risking Trumpian wrath.
docs.snippet: With many Republicans courting the president and others afraid to criticize him, an Ohio congressman has gingerly created a small crack in the wall, risking Trumpian wrath.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — A low-profile Republican congressman from northeast Ohio has gone where few in his party have dared this campaign season: He has bragged to his constituents that he has stood up to President Trump.

headline.main: Anomaly or Omen? A House Republican Tells Voters He ‘Stood Up’ to Trump
headline.print_headline: Republican Says, I ‘Stood Up’ to Trump

docs.abstract: What was billed as a photo opportunity quickly turned into a heated confrontation between President Trump and the Democratic leaders of Congress, Nancy Pelosi and Chuck Schumer.
docs.snippet: What was billed as a photo opportunity quickly turned into a heated confrontation between President Trump and the Democratic leaders of Congress, Nancy Pelosi and Chuck Schumer.
docs.lead_paragraph: In another time, the Washington photo opportunity was a steady ritual. Leaders smiled, usually sitting in well-stuffed chairs, at least feigning smiles for the cameras. Pleasantries were spoken. The main objective was to get the picture and say as little as possible.

headline.main: 5 Takeaways From Trump’s Meeting With Pelosi and Schumer

docs.abstract: As lawmakers negotiate a deal, Republicans are warning the president that declaring an emergency to build a wall could rupture his party and prompt a vote to overrule him.
docs.snippet: As lawmakers negotiate a deal, Republicans are warning the president that declaring an emergency to build a wall could rupture his party and prompt a vote to overrule him.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump’s legislative path to a border wall has narrowed significantly on the eve of Tuesday’s State of the Union speech, and his fallback plan to circumvent Congress by declaring a state of emergency could create a major division in his own party.

headline.main: Trump’s Options for Wall Shrink as Republicans Balk at National Emergency Declaration
headline.print_headline: Trump’s Options for Wall Shrink as G.O.P. Wavers

byline.original: By Glenn Thrush and Emily Cochrane

docs.abstract: Vice President Mike Pence led an administration negotiation with congressional aides from both parties, and another meeting is scheduled for Sunday, though there was little hope of any breakthrough.
docs.snippet: Vice President Mike Pence led an administration negotiation with congressional aides from both parties, and another meeting is scheduled for Sunday, though there was little hope of any breakthrough.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — As a partial government shutdown entered its third week, negotiations between Vice President Mike Pence and congressional aides from both parties yielded little progress on Saturday while the impact on government services and on federal workers was worsening by the day.

headline.main: Trump Says ‘Not Much Headway’ in Talks as Shutdown Enters Third Week
headline.print_headline: Talk of Security Priorities, But Little Hope of Progress

byline.original: By Michael Tackett and Catie Edmondson

docs.abstract: Among famous figures in sports, entertainment and politics, Ms. Adelson, a prominent Republican donor and the wife of the casino magnate Sheldon Adelson, stands out.
docs.snippet: Among famous figures in sports, entertainment and politics, Ms. Adelson, a prominent Republican donor and the wife of the casino magnate Sheldon Adelson, stands out.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump on Friday awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom, the nation’s highest civilian commendation, to an eclectic mix of honorees from the worlds of sports, entertainment, law and politics, including two of the most famous names of the last century, Babe Ruth and Elvis Presley.

headline.main: Trump Awards Medals of Freedom to Elvis, Babe Ruth and Miriam Adelson
headline.print_headline: Among Medal of Freedom Honorees, a Big Donor Stands Out

docs.abstract: Federal law prohibits strikes, public servants care about their work and other reasons airports and prisons aren’t in chaos, despite a protracted federal shutdown.
docs.snippet: Federal law prohibits strikes, public servants care about their work and other reasons airports and prisons aren’t in chaos, despite a protracted federal shutdown.
docs.lead_paragraph: Several hundred thousand federal workers keep showing up at their jobs every day — screening luggage for explosives, policing prisons, preparing to open tax filing season — even though they aren’t getting paid. You wouldn’t expect that at a private company or, say, in almost any European country. But they keep reporting for work, in the midst of what is now the longest federal shutdown in United States history.

headline.main: Why Don’t Unpaid Federal Workers Walk Off the Job?
headline.print_headline: Why Don’t They Just Stop Coming Into Work?

byline.original: By Jim Tankersley and Thomas Kaplan

docs.abstract: Restaurants have fed them without charge. Banks have suspended late fees on their credit cards. And at airports, they’ve been offered hugs, encouragement and casseroles.
docs.snippet: Restaurants have fed them without charge. Banks have suspended late fees on their credit cards. And at airports, they’ve been offered hugs, encouragement and casseroles.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — When the government shut down in late December, Morgan McKay offered free pizza and wine to furloughed and otherwise unpaid federal workers at her popular Denver restaurant, Oblio’s.

headline.main: As Shutdown Drags On, Some Step Up to Help Unpaid Federal Workers
headline.print_headline: Offering a Hand, Even a Hug, As the Shutdown Lumbers On

byline.original: By Glenn Thrush, Julie Bosman and Kirk Johnson

docs.abstract: The administration is opening the government piece by piece, forcing thousands of workers to report to the job without pay in sectors that could benefit the president’s base.
docs.snippet: The administration is opening the government piece by piece, forcing thousands of workers to report to the job without pay in sectors that could benefit the president’s base.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — As the government shutdown stretches into its fourth week, the Trump administration is reinterpreting longstanding rules to open the federal government piece by piece, forcing thousands of workers to report to work without pay, many of them in sectors that could minimize damage to the president’s base.

headline.main: White House Redefines Who Is Essential to Get Parts of Government Moving Again
headline.print_headline: More Are Deemed ‘Essential’ to Get Parts of Government Moving Again

byline.original: By Katie Rogers and Alan Rappeport
